---
import CodexLayout from "../../layouts/CodexLayout.astro";
import "../../styles/tips-shared.css";
---

<CodexLayout
  title="Codex CLI Tips & Tricks — Power User Guide"
  description="instructions.md, approval modes, exec mode, sub-agents, CI patterns, and mistakes to avoid with Codex CLI."
  currentPage="tips"
>
  <div class="tips-wrapper">

    <header class="tips-hero">
      <span class="tips-hero__eyebrow">Codex CLI · Power User</span>
      <h1 class="tips-hero__title">
        Tips &amp; <span class="tips-hero__accent">Tricks</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="tips-hero__desc">Instructions file, approval modes, exec mode for CI, sub-agents, and the mistakes that waste the most time.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="tips-section">
      <div class="tips-section__header">
        <span class="tips-section__icon">⚡</span>
        <h2 class="tips-section__title">Quick Wins</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tips-cards">

        <div class="tips-card tips-card--highlight">
          <span class="tips-card__num">01</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">.codex/instructions.md is your foundation</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Write it once. Codex reads it every run. Put your stack, conventions, testing patterns, and rules here. It's the difference between a tool that guesses and one that knows your codebase.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-card">
          <span class="tips-card__num">02</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">exec for one-shot CI runs</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Non-interactive mode. Perfect for automation, CI pipelines, and scripted tasks.</p>
          <div class="tips-card__cmd">codex exec "run tests and fix any failing ones"</div>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-card">
          <span class="tips-card__num">03</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">Approval mode determines autonomy</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Three modes: <code>suggest</code> (show changes, ask), <code>auto</code> (apply without asking), <code>full-auto</code> (run commands too). Match to your trust level.</p>
          <div class="tips-card__cmd">codex "task" --approval-mode auto</div>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-card">
          <span class="tips-card__num">04</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">Commit before big tasks</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Codex reads your git history as part of its context. A clean commit before a big task also gives you a clear rollback point if you don't like the output.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-card">
          <span class="tips-card__num">05</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">Feed it the whole repo</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Don't point Codex at one file. It builds a mental model of your whole codebase and makes better decisions when it has full context.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-card">
          <span class="tips-card__num">06</span>
          <div class="tips-card__title">--quiet for clean script output</div>
          <p class="tips-card__desc">Suppresses the "thinking" output for cleaner integration into shell pipelines and CI logs.</p>
          <div class="tips-card__cmd">codex --quiet exec "task"</div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tips-section">
      <div class="tips-section__header">
        <span class="tips-section__icon">🔍</span>
        <h2 class="tips-section__title">Hidden Features</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tips-features">

        <div class="tips-feature">
          <span class="tips-feature__icon">🤖</span>
          <div class="tips-feature__body">
            <div class="tips-feature__title">Built-in sub-agent support</div>
            <p class="tips-feature__desc">For large tasks, Codex can spawn parallel worker agents automatically. It handles the orchestration — you don't need to break the task up manually. Just describe the full scope and it figures out the parallelism.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-feature">
          <span class="tips-feature__icon">🔗</span>
          <div class="tips-feature__body">
            <div class="tips-feature__title">Give it a URL — it fetches and reads</div>
            <p class="tips-feature__desc">You can reference a URL in your task description and Codex will fetch and read it as context. Useful for "implement this API according to the spec at https://..."</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-feature">
          <span class="tips-feature__icon">🔄</span>
          <div class="tips-feature__body">
            <div class="tips-feature__title">Swap models with --model</div>
            <p class="tips-feature__desc">Use a different model for different tasks without changing config. Fast model for exploration, smarter model for production code.</p>
            <code class="tips-feature__cmd">codex --model gpt-4o-mini "quick refactor of this function"</code>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-feature">
          <span class="tips-feature__icon">🙈</span>
          <div class="tips-feature__body">
            <div class="tips-feature__title">Respects .gitignore</div>
            <p class="tips-feature__desc">Codex won't explore files that match your .gitignore patterns. node_modules, dist, and .env are automatically excluded — no extra configuration needed.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tips-section">
      <div class="tips-section__header">
        <span class="tips-section__icon">💀</span>
        <h2 class="tips-section__title">Common Mistakes</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tips-gotchas">

        <div class="tips-gotcha">
          <span class="tips-gotcha__skull">☠️</span>
          <div class="tips-gotcha__title">No .codex/instructions.md</div>
          <p class="tips-gotcha__desc">Codex flies blind without it. It will make assumptions about your stack that are often wrong, and you'll spend time correcting it on every task.</p>
          <span class="tips-gotcha__fix">Create it before your first real task. It takes 10 minutes and pays back immediately.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-gotcha">
          <span class="tips-gotcha__skull">☠️</span>
          <div class="tips-gotcha__title">--full-auto on unfamiliar repos</div>
          <p class="tips-gotcha__desc">full-auto runs commands without asking — including potentially destructive ones. On repos you don't fully understand, this can cause real damage.</p>
          <span class="tips-gotcha__fix">Use suggest or auto on unknown codebases. Reserve full-auto for your own trusted projects.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="tips-gotcha">
          <span class="tips-gotcha__skull">☠️</span>
          <div class="tips-gotcha__title">Missing OPENAI_API_KEY</div>
          <p class="tips-gotcha__desc">Some versions fail silently or with a confusing error when the key isn't set. Always confirm your key is exported before running.</p>
          <span class="tips-gotcha__fix">Add to .zshrc: export OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-... and reload your shell.</span>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tips-section">
      <div class="tips-section__header">
        <span class="tips-section__icon">🔄</span>
        <h2 class="tips-section__title">Workflow Combos</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tips-recipes">

        <div class="tips-recipe">
          <div class="tips-recipe__header">
            <span class="tips-recipe__icon">🏭</span>
            <span class="tips-recipe__name">CI auto-fix on failing tests</span>
          </div>
          <div class="tips-recipe__body">
            <p class="tips-recipe__desc">Run Codex in CI to automatically attempt fixes on test failures, then commit the result for human review.</p>
            <div class="tips-recipe__steps">
              <div class="tips-recipe__step"><span class="tips-recipe__step-num">1.</span><span class="tips-recipe__step-text">Add <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> to CI secrets</span></div>
              <div class="tips-recipe__step"><span class="tips-recipe__step-num">2.</span><span class="tips-recipe__step-text">On test failure: <code>codex exec --quiet "the test suite is failing, fix the failing tests without changing test logic" --approval-mode auto</code></span></div>
              <div class="tips-recipe__step"><span class="tips-recipe__step-num">3.</span><span class="tips-recipe__step-text">Open a PR with the changes for human review. Codex does the grunt work, you approve the fix.</span></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</CodexLayout>
